<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="87" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[718,1311,2233,2655]" pageId="6" pageNumber="87">
Phylogenetically, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forster" authorityYear="1778" box="[977,1116,2308,2341]" class="Mammalia" family="Dipodidae" genus="Orientallactaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="6" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sibirica">O. sibirica</taxonomicName>
is the sister species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="G. M. Allen" authorityYear="1925" box="[885,1023,2347,2380]" class="Mammalia" family="Dipodidae" genus="Orientallactaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="6" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bullata">O. bullata</taxonomicName>
. Genetic data provide some evidence that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forster" authorityYear="1778" box="[1085,1218,2387,2420]" class="Mammalia" family="Dipodidae" genus="Orientallactaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="6" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sibirica">O. sibirica</taxonomicName>
is not a single species but a complex of cryptic species; however, specific descriptions and distributions of these species are not yet clear. Nine subspecies recognized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
